        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">‘Duckwings’ and ‘piles’ are mentioned as game breeds of fowl in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 227. In Carus trans. 1868, 1: 279, the former is translated as ‘entenflüglige’ with the original English term in parentheses, while the latter term is left untranslated.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In Carus trans. 1868, 1: 282, ‘spangled’ is translated as ‘geflitterte’ and ‘pencilled’ as ‘gestrichelte’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">In Carus trans. 1868, 1: 314, ‘hackles’ is translated as ‘die Schuppenfedern’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 230.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Drechsler and the book on fowl breeding have not been identified. In Carus trans. 1868, 1: 284, ‘sooty fowl’ is translated as ‘schwarzes Huhn’.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Carus had requested proof-sheets from CD in his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5625.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter to CD of 11 September 1867</ref>; the German publisher, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Christian Friedrich Schweizerbart</ref>, had made the same request of CD’s publisher, John Murray (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5633.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Murray, 23 September [1867]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">Carus refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3504.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Gottlob Neumeister’s</ref> book on pigeon breeding (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5834.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Neumeister 1837</ref>), which CD had recently sent him (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5628.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. V. Carus, 16 September 1867</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
